The Carlist Party, known in Spanish as *Partido Carlista*, in Catalan as *Partit Carlí*, in Basque as *Karlista Alderdia*, in Galician as *Partido Carlista*, and in Asturian as *Partíu Carlista* (PC), is a [Spanish political party](/List_of_political_parties_in_Spain) that purports to be the contemporary manifestation of the historical tradition of [Carlism](/Carlism). Its formal establishment dates to 1970, though it operated in illegality until 1977, emerging into the open following the death of the [caudillo](/Caudillo) [Francisco Franco](/Francisco_Franco) and the subsequent [democratisation of Spain](/Spanish_transition_to_democracy).

Since the year 2000, the role of general secretary has been held by Evaristo Olcina, and the party's official publication is *El Federal*. Its political orientation is firmly situated within the [left](/Left-wing_politics), advocating for [workers' self-management](/Workers%27_self-management) and [confederalism](/Confederalism). A significant annual event organized by the party is the commemoration at [Montejurra](/Montejurra). The Carlist Party operates on a federal structure, allowing for the formation of sovereign Carlist parties within the associate nationalities of its framework. The youth organizations of the various Carlist parties and groups are consolidated under the umbrella of Carlist Youths (*Juventudes Carlistas*). Notably, the Carlist Party distinguishes itself as the left-wing faction of the broader Carlist movement, which has historically been characterized by its [right-wing](/Right-wing_politics) and [conservative](/Conservatism) leanings.

The party gained particular recognition for its support of [Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma](/Carlos_Hugo,_Duke_of_Parma) as the legitimate leader of the Carlist movement, over his brother.

### History

The genesis of the current Carlist Party can be traced back to the ideological rejuvenation of the then-illegal [Traditionalist Communion](/Traditionalist_Communion). This transformation began during the 1950s and 1960s, a period when [Carlism](/Carlism) was suppressed and prohibited within [Francoist Spain](/Francoist_Spain). The movement coalesced within university and worker organizations that were not integrated into the Francoist regime's sole official party. These nascent groups, such as the Group of Traditionalist Students (AET) for the university sector and the Traditionalist Worker's Movement (MOT) for workers, operated under the patronage of prince [Carlos Hugo, Duke of Parma](/Carlos_Hugo,_Duke_of_Parma). While the specific name "Carlist Party" did not materialize until the late 1960s, its foundational elements were being forged during this era of clandestine activity.

Between 1970 and 1972, the Carlist Party convened Congresses of the Carlist People in [Arbonne](/Arbonne). These gatherings marked a pivotal moment, as they adopted a program aimed at fundamentally altering Carlism's ideology. The objective was to steer it towards [self-management socialism](/Workers%27_self-management) and to transform the Carlist Party into a mass, class-based, federal, and democratic entity. This new vision aspired to a monarchy grounded in socialism, established through a pact between the dynastic line and the populace. The leader, Francesc Xavier, following a severe automobile accident, relinquished full authority to his son, Carlos Hugo. Carlos Hugo, acting through his representative in Spain, [José María de Zavala](/Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Zavala_Castella), assumed control of the party and formally resigned his leadership on April 20, 1975.

According to the party's own records, it boasted approximately 25,000 members in 1977. In 1974, the Carlist Party forged an alliance with other opposition forces within the [Democratic Junta of Spain](/Democratic_Junta_of_Spain). This coalition, however, dissolved in February 1975, leading the Carlist Party to join the [Democratic Convergence Platform](/Democratic_Convergence_Platform). This platform subsequently merged with the Democratic Junta in March 1976, forming the Democratic Co-ordination.

[José María Zavala](/Jos%C3%A9_Mar%C3%ADa_Zavala_Castella)

The party was unable to participate in the inaugural [democratic elections of 1977](/Spanish_general_election,_1977) as it had not secured official recognition as a political party in a timely manner. Concurrently, [Prince Sixtus Henry of Bourbon-Parma](/Prince_Sixtus_Henry_of_Bourbon-Parma) lent his support to elements loyal to [Francoism](/Francoism). With the assistance of international [far-right](/Far-right_politics) sympathizers, he endeavored to establish an alternative Carlist movement, distinct from the Carlist Party and aligned with the far-right, drawing considerable backing from [New Force](/New_Force_(Spain)). Following a meeting with some of his adherents, they proceeded to disrupt and intimidate their opposition with considerable force. This culminated in a violent assault during the annual Carlist gathering at [Montejurra in 1976](/Montejurra_Incidents), an event tragically marked by the deaths of two Carlist partisans.

Following its endorsement of the [Spanish Constitution of 1978](/Spanish_Constitution_of_1978), the Carlist Party experienced a significant internal schism, fracturing into [nationalist](/Nationalism) and [left-wing](/Left-wing_politics) factions. In the [1979 Spanish general election](/Spanish_general_election,_1979), the party garnered 50,552 votes, representing 0.28% of the total, and failed to secure any parliamentary representation. Its most notable electoral performance was in [Navarre](/Navarre_(Congress_of_Deputies_constituency)), where it achieved 7.72% of the vote, and in the [Basque Country](/Basque_Country_(autonomous_community)), with 0.65%. The internal strife over electoral strategy led to the resignation of its general secretary, Zavala, along with other directors, amidst a leadership dispute between Carlos Carnicero and Josep Carles Clemente. In April of that same year, the party secured 12,165 votes (4.79%) in the elections for the [Parliament of Navarre](/Parliament_of_Navarre), winning one seat. However, the representative elected did not attend parliamentary sessions. In November 1979, Carlos Hugo relinquished the party presidency. By April 1980, his influence within the party had waned considerably, despite not renouncing his dynastic claims to the [Spanish Crown](/Spanish_Crown), a claim he had held since his father's abdication in 1975. His position within the Spanish political landscape had, by this point, become largely testimonial.

[Mariano Zufia](/Mariano_Zuf%C3%ADa_Urrizalqui), who served as the general secretary of the [Carlist Party of Euskal Herria](/Carlist_Party_of_Euskal_Herria) and was a member of the Navarrese parliament, assumed the leadership position of General Secretary of the Carlist Party. In 1986, he was instrumental in the formation of [United Left](/United_Left_(Spain)), though he subsequently withdrew from the coalition in 1987. The Carlist Party subsequently faced significant challenges in participating in most subsequent electoral processes, largely due to a deficit in both funding and active membership. In 1989, it was among the political parties and signing associations that formed the Pact of Estella. By 2005, the party actively campaigned against the proposed [European Constitution](/Treaty_establishing_a_Constitution_for_Europe).

The Carlist Party has maintained a consistent stance of opposition to Spain's two dominant political forces: the [People's Party](/People%27s_Party_(Spain)) and the [Spanish Socialist Workers' Party](/Spanish_Socialist_Workers%27_Party). [1]

### Ideology

The ideological underpinnings of the Carlist Party are deeply rooted in [Catholic social teaching](/Catholic_social_teaching) and the principles of the [Christian Left](/Christian_left). However, the party does not restrict its membership solely to practicing Catholics, acknowledging "the reality of the secularization of modern society." This stance allows the party to derive its critiques of contemporary society from these Catholic tenets, rather than imposing them as dogma. It defines its political position as part of the "New Left," which rejects the state-controlled economic models exemplified by the Soviet Union in favor of a democratized market structure, emphasizing cooperatives and trade unions. The Carlists' critique of capitalism stems from an opposition to [Liberal individualism](/Liberal_individualism), advocating instead for [Catholic Personalism](/Personalism). [2]

The Carlist Party champions both democracy and socialism, viewing them as essential bulwarks against, respectively, fascism and liberalism (with which it associates capitalism). [3] It actively supports a range of social justice initiatives, including the legalization of homosexuality [4] and the protection of [ethnic minority rights](/Minority_rights). [5] Crucially, these positions are justified not from a secular liberal standpoint, but rather from a distinctly Catholic perspective. [6]

